P&C Pricing Tutorial

Pricing Example

I have created this document to show the work I have done and as a first starting point for discussion. Any suggestions or advice is, of course, more than welcome.

The outline of the document is as follows:

  1. Import and description of the dataset
  2. One-Way tables and KPI
  3. Fit Frequency Model
  4. Fit Severity Model
  5. Combine the models
  6. Evaluate Performances
  7. Future Improvements

Import the data

The dataset used for modeling is the dataset that can be created using the script data-fetch.R, data-prep.R and feature-engineering.R from the main repository. For simplicity I included the dataset as an RDS file in this repository, modeling_data.RDS

The data can therefore be imported with the command:

modeling_data <- readRDS("./modeling_data.RDS") %>% ungroup() %>% na.omit()

I am also ungrouping the dataset and deleting any observation with NAs. The dataset comes from a grouping process and therefore it is handy to ungroup it since in the analysis I will modify grouping variables. This operation would not be allowed on a grouped dataframe.

We can check that all the operation performed as expected:

map(modeling_data, ~sum(is.na(.)))

and the relative plots:

At this point we can divide the dataset in train/test (.8, .2) and add the necessary variables:

modeling_data <- modeling_data %>% 
                 mutate(sev = if_else(claim_count == 0, 0, claim_amount / claim_count),
                        lc = claim_amount / exposure) %>%
                 mutate(id = row_number())

train_data <- modeling_data %>% sample_frac(.8) 

test_data <- modeling_data %>% anti_join(train_data, by = "id")

We can now start the modeling process.

Fit Frequency Model

The first model we are going to fit is the frequncy model.

This model will be a GLM with target variable claim count

freq_model <- glm(claim_count ~ region + sex + age_range + vehicle_age + make +
                    vehicle_category + offset(log(exposure)),
                  family = poisson(link = "log"),
                  data = train_data
                  )

summary(freq_model)

Fit Severity Model

Similarly, we fit a glm for the severity.

Here the variable target will be sev.

In this case, the variable sex has not been included, since the level Juridica does not have any claims.

sev_model <- glm(sev ~ region + age_range + vehicle_age + make +
                    vehicle_category,
                 family = Gamma(link = "log"),
                 weights = claim_count,
                 data = filter(train_data, claim_count > 0)
)

Combine the models

It is handy to combine the two models in a single one that predict the loss cost.

This can be done with the following code:

train_data <- train_data %>% 
              mutate(pred_numbers = predict(freq_model, newdata = train_data, type = "response"),
                     pred_sev = predict(sev_model, newdata = train_data, type = "response"),
                     pred_lc = pred_numbers * pred_sev / exposure)

lc_model <- glm(pred_lc ~ region + sex + age_range + vehicle_age + make +
                  vehicle_category,
                family = Gamma(link = "log"),
                weights = exposure,
                data = train_data
)

This, of course, will lead to the same results as multyplig the frequency adn severity models.

sum(predict(lc_model, newdata = train_data, type = "response"))
## [1] 597562045
sum(train_data$pred_lc)
## [1] 597562045

Future Improvements

As mentioned, this is just a preliminary work. Future improvement could include, estimating relativities, exploring interactions between factors and using splines or any other smoothing function for numerical predictors.
